Fig. 10
(a-b) shows the thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) of neat XNBR latex and XNBR latex with different concentration of CDs. Fig. 10 (a) shows the plot between weight (%) vs. temperature. From Fig. 10 (a), it is seen that the onset of degradation value (Ti) of XNBR latex increases from 379 °C to 419 °C with an increase in the concentration of CDs from 0.1 to 4 phr (Table 4
). The reason for the increase in onset of degradation temperature (Ti) can be due to the repositioning of CDs particle at the air-polymer interface. This will as a heat shield thus delaying the heat transfer from the external environment to the XNBR latex [45]. The residue at 800 °C of XNBR latex slightly increases with increase in CDs concentration (Table 4). Fig. 10 (b) displays the plot between derivative weight (%/min) vs. temperature. From Fig. 10 (b), it is seen that Tmax (temperature at which maximum degradation takes place) value of XNBR latex significantly increases with the increase in concentration of CDs up to 1 phr (Tmax values of neat XNBR latex and XNBR latex with 1 phr of CDs concentration is 458 °C and 469 °C respectively) (Table 4). However, T max value starts to decrease after 2 phr of CDs concentration (Tmax values of XNBR latex with 2 phr and 4 phr of CDs concentration is 460 °C and 458 °C respectively) (Table 4). The increase in the maximum degradation temperature (Tmax) at lower concentration of CDs can be attributed to the result of absorption of the free radicals generated during polymer decomposition by the activated carbon surface. At higher temperatures or higher loadings (above 1 phr CDs) the decomposition of oxidized CDs surface can counteract the stabilizing effect [46]. In addition, the rate of degradation at Tmax gradually decreases (reduction in the height of Tmax value) with increase in CDs concentration (Table 4). The significant improvement in the mechanical, rheological and thermal stability of XNBR latex by adding very low concentration of CDs is attributed to the good dispersion of CDs in XNBR latex which arises from the covalent conjugation between the CDs and XNBR latex (as discussed in the earlier section).
